The optical inactivity of solutions of antitartaric aeid has been explained hitherto by supposing that the actions on the polarised light of the two symmetrical halves of the molecule are diametrieally opposed although numerically equal. There takes place,¹ as the phrase goeS‚ an internal compensation of the opposed actions of the right and left asymmetrical carbon atonis contained in the same mole- cule, as each half of the molecule is the mirrored image of the other.

Such an explanation may indeed hold good as long as we deal with solutions of antitartaric acid prepared hy using solvents which do not cause electrolytical dissociation.
